The premiere of the sci-fi classic #DuneMovie is provoking fresh thoughts on our relationship with water and drylands here on Earth.

Deserts are classified by scientists as drylands::: an environmental category that also includes grasslands::: steppes and savannas. Even though they make up 40 percent of our planet‚Äôs landmasses::: drylands are increasingly threatened by public misconceptions about them. These false perceptions‚Äîperpetuated by pop culture‚Äîcondemn a dry environment as a wasteland.

To navigate the challenges of the 21st century::: we need to understand and protect drylands as critical shared resources for humans and many other species to survive and thrive.

ASU's Global Drylands Center uses simulations of the future to better understand the drylands::: and human adaptation and resilience.

Learn more about ASU‚Äôs Global Drylands Center and their mission: http://ow.ly/GySR50GwqhJ

üéì In 1928::: Love Hatton Jordan became the first Black woman to graduate from ASU.

üéì In 1963::: Jesse Wilmer Jones became the first Black student to earn a PhD at ASU.

üìö In May 1966::: John Edwards made history as ASU's first Black professor::: with an appointment in the School of Education. I had a suggestion about a certain director whose omission from several film critic discussions in relation to his contributions to Arizona is often the case. His omission in a recent Arizona Republic article on films made in Arizona inspired me to write this...........
.He was cantankerous::: blunt::: demanding and could drive his actors nuts. But John Ford was the consummate director. He began in the silent era with one of the early film cowboys::: Harry Carey Sr.::: as well as George O‚ÄôBrien::: and eventually molding the careers of John Wayne and Henry Fonda as the cinema moved into the sound era. And it was Ford‚Äôs impact on the film history of Arizona that is most significant. But Ford‚Äôs impact on Arizona doesn‚Äôt actually begin with John Ford himself. Another man gets that credit for altering the story of film making in Arizona.
In the 1930‚Äôs a man named Harry Goulding::: proprietor of the Goulding Trading Lodge in Northeast Arizona‚Äôs Navajo Reservation had an idea. In the book ‚ÄúJohn Ford and the American West:::‚Äù by Peter Cowie::: Goulding was described as ‚ÄúA tall::: lanky cowboy in the style of Gary Cooper::: hailing from Colorado.‚Äù How fitting. Goulding‚Äôs idea was to plant himself on the door step of John Ford‚Äôs office and pitch the beautiful vistas of Monument Valley to the director::: known for his love of sweeping landscapes and rugged Western terrain matching his style of films. Goulding put together a portfolio of photographs produced by German photographer Josef Muench of ‚ÄúArizona Highways‚Äù fame. Ford and his producer::: Walter Wanger::: were immediately enthralled with the breathtaking photographs. His efforts of bluffing his way into the director‚Äôs office paid off. And one group who would be the beneficiaries of the relationship that developed were the Native American tribes in the Four Corners area. Cowie referenced a quote provided by Ford‚Äôs grandson Dan::: ‚ÄúMalnutrition::: disease::: unemployment and alcoholism were the Four Horsemen of the Navajo‚Äôs apocalypse.‚Äù The Ford and Goulding partnership helped the Navajo nation considerably::: providing food::: supplies::: aid and medicine to the tribes and most importantly::: jobs::: on both sides of the camera::: giving Ford's Westerns much authenticity.
Troubling to me is how often the John Ford story is overlooked by so many newer film critics::: writers and commentators. In a recent Arizona Republic article entitled ‚ÄúThese movies were made in Arizona; how to watch:::‚Äù several dozen films were listed but not one Ford film was in the mix. It is an extreme sin of omission. Arizona Historian::: Marshall Trimble said ‚ÄúThese writers today have no ‚Äôsense of Arizona.‚Äô" Films like ‚ÄúThe Searchers::: My Darling Clementine:::" and ‚ÄúStagecoach:::‚Äù are essential additions to any film list::: and that is just the beginning.
Sharing the Arizona spotlight is Sedona::: as well as a former movie set near Mesa::: Arizona called Apacheland. And one of the most important sites::: is::: of course::: Old Tucson. In 1940 the first film made in that Tucson movie ranch was a film called ‚ÄúArizona‚Äù starring Jean Arthur and a very young William Holden. It was missing as well from the list.
Arizona was also used for the film adaptation in 1955 of the musical ‚ÄúOklahoma.‚Äù Due to some overdevelopment
in the state with the film‚Äôs namesake::: it was moved to locations near Nogales::: Arizona for its similarity to Oklahoma. Many sites in Arizona are effective facimilies to other locations they are utilized to represent. Old Tucson has been located in Texas numerous times.
And it all began with the famed director::: his huge troupe of actors including Wayne::: Fonda::: Ward Bond::: Victor McLaglen::: Paul Fix::: Ken Curtis and many::: many::: more::: and that cowboy from Colorado. Eventually the Northeastern Arizona sites would be expanded to include the Moab::: Utah area and Wayne::: Fonda::: Jimmy Stewart::: Richard Widmark and others would continue the location work in so many Ford films. And the films of other directors as well.
It seems to be a shame to leave one of the most important parts of the Arizona story out of the discussion of films in Arizona.

Charles Lopresto

column5: The financial aid department in this school is extremely incompetent. I have never experienced such a cumbersome::: non communicative::: and disregarding group in financial aid services (this is my 15th year in school::: and my 6th school). Financial aid is such an important part of a school::: yet your financial aid department does not return student emails::: they make you wait in line on the phone (450 callers ahead of you::: 560 callers ahead of you::: 742 callers ahead of you that was last night) and then call you back at their convenience the next day. Then they close out the case if you can not answer when they call you back (as opposed to actually trying to resolve the issue by calling you back several times in the day). Then you have to play the call in and wait game again. They do not bother looking farther into your case when you submit a case::: I was told on the several occasions that I called in that my aid was fine::: and they were just waiting for the funds from the government. Then on the 7th they rescinded my aid::: did not tell me they had done that or why::: and I had to try to get a hold of someone else to find out. Of coursed the 24 hr service does not know anything::: they are apparently volunteers that only have access to read the notes::: of which are so vague they say nothing about what is going on. I was told to fill out some for to get my aid back::: and the guy could not answer any of my questions (this was on the chat system). I finally realized they had applied or standard student loans::: but not grad plus. So::: no one in the FA office could bother themselves with making sure i even had direct loans available in the last four months you have been telling me my aid was fine?????? I did my grad plus counseling and had it sent to the school::: that did not cause any of them to look deeper into my financial aid?????? I attempted to go through the Student Aid system to apply for my Grad Plus loan::: but the system stated that you do not use the student aid system to apply for such grants (this would be a good idea to join::: since your financial aid department can not seem to do their job). However::: you also do not work with your students to get them funded::: I am now without funding for my courses::: I can not get a hold of anyone to fix the problem::: and I will have to drop your program by the 26th of January. I can not get into another school this late in the semester::: so over all your financial aid department has harmed me and your school does not seem to care. This experience has been very dissatisfying to say the least. I would not recommend your school to anyone.
